Partition sizing — the unit of parallelism.

A partition is processed by exactly one task, on one executor core. So the partition count is your parallelism — and getting it wrong hurts in two directions.

Too few partitions, and your cores sit idle. One slow task stalls the whole stage, and a single huge partition risks an out-of-memory error.

Too many partitions, and task-scheduling overhead takes over. The tiny tasks finish in milliseconds, while the scheduler spends longer setting them up than the actual work takes.

So here are the rules of thumb. On a production cluster, target somewhere between one hundred twenty-eight and two hundred fifty-six megabytes per partition. In local mode, two to four times the number of see-pee-you cores is plenty. And after a shuffle, the count is set by the shuffle-partitions setting, which defaults to two hundred — and we tune that next.

Finally, two ways to inspect. You can ask a dataframe how many partitions it currently has, with dataframe dot R-D-D dot get-num-partitions. And you can look at how the rows are distributed, using the spark-partition-id function.
